f Norman origin): habitational name from either of two minor places in France called Digny (in Eure-et-Loir and Loiret).","Irish: from Gaelic <b>Mac an Deaghánaigh</b> ‘son of the deacon’ (see   Deane  )."]},{"name":"Deacon","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>deken</i>, <i>dicoun</i> ‘deacon, a priest's assistant at church services’ (Old French <i>diacne</i>, Old English <i>diacon</i>, <i>dēacon</i>, both ultimately from Late Latin <i>diaconus</i>, from Greek <i>diakonos</i> ‘servant’). Since deacons were in holy orders they would not be permitted to marry (with allowance for those few already married when ordained), so the surname is probably in most cases a secular nickname rather than the name of a church official, perhaps denoting a deacon's servant.","English: variant of   Dicken  .","Irish (Wexford): of English origin (see 1 and 2 above), taken to Ireland in the 17th century. When the Irish surname is not of English origin, it may be an Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Ó Deocáin</b> ‘descendant of <i>Deocán</i>’, a personal name of uncertain etymology."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"John Deane was born about 1570, in England, United Kingdom. He married Joan Fuller on 22 August 1622, in Caversham, Oxfordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons and 3 daughters. He died on 19 June 1643, in Caversham, Oxfordshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 74."},"et":{"about 1570–19 June 1643":"umbes 1570–19. juuni 1643","1574–1670":"1574–1670","1596–1643":"1596–1643","1623–Female":"1623–Surnud","1625–Female":"1625–Surnud","1631–Female":"1631–Surnud","1637–Male":"1637–Surnud","1570–1643":"1570–1643","1623":"1623","22 AUG 1622":"22. august 1622","1643":"1643","1631":"1631","1596":"1596","1574":"1574","19 June 1643":"19. juuni 1643","1670":"1670","1570":"1570","about 1570":"umbes 1570","1637":"1637","1625":"1625","Caversham, 